  "text": "Despite these theories, by the end of the decade, quantitative easing was a widely established policy. The crash of the mortgage-backed security (MBS) market forced the US Federal Reserve to buy a trillion dollars of toxic MBSs lest the economy's liquidity continue to deteriorate [CITATION_1] . A similar policy was undertaken by the Bank of England, which bought 3 200 billion pounds of gilts (long-term government bonds) from households to ease credit conditions (Joyce et al. 2011 ).",
